//purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Totality for Kids is the second collection of poems by Joshua Clover, whose debut, Madonna anno domini, won the Walt Whitman award from the Academy of American Poets. This volume takes as its subject the troubled sleep of late modernity, from the grandeur and failure of megacities to the retreats and displacements of the suburbs. The power of crowds and architecture commingles with the alienation and idleness of the observer, caught between "the brutal red dream/Of the collective" and "the parade/Of the ideal citizen." The book’s action takes place in these gaps, "dead spaces beside the endlessly grieving stream." The frozen tableau of the spectacle meets its double in the sense that something is always about to happen. Political furies and erotic imaginings coalesce and escape within a welter of unmoored allusions, encounters, citations, and histories, the dreams possible within the modern’s excess of signification—as if to return revolutionary possibility to the regime of information by singing it its own song.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAmerican poetry. 7aPOETRY / General.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aalienation.  aallusions.  aamerica.  aamerican literature.  aamerican poetry.  aamerican poets.  aarchitecture.  aart and literature.  aaspiring poets.  aaward winner.  acontemporary poetry.  acontemporary poets.  aenglish majors.  aeroticism.  alit students.  aliterary critics.  aliterary studies.  amodern histories.  amodern perspective.  amodern poets.  amodernity.  aobservations.  apoems.  apoetry collection.  apoetry.  apolitical poems.  asleep issues.  asuburban landscape.  asuburbs.  atroubled sleep.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Ca